debounce.response:
To prevent your search input from firing an API call on every single keystroke, you need **debouncing**. Debouncing ensures that the API call is made only after the user stops typing for a specified delay (e.g., 300ms). This reduces server load and improves performance.

Here’s how to implement it in vanilla JavaScript.

---

## 1. Create a reusable debounce function

The core idea is to wrap your API call inside a function that clears the previous timeout and sets a new one each time the event triggers.

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timeoutId;

  // Return a new function that wraps the original
  return function(...args) {
    // Clear the previous timer
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);

    // Set a new timer
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
      func.apply(this, args);
    }, delay);
  };
}
```

- `func`: the function you want to execute (your API call).
- `delay`: the wait time in milliseconds after the last keystroke.

---

## 2. Apply it to your search input

Assume you have an `<input>` with an event listener that currently calls `fetchResults(query)` on every `input` event.

```html
<input type="text" id="search" placeholder="Search..." />
```

### Before (problematic)
```javascript
document.getElementById('search').addEventListener('input', (e) => {
  fetchResults(e.target.value);   // ❌ fires on every keystroke
});
```

### After (debounced)
```javascript
const searchInput = document.getElementById('search');

// Debounced version of your API call
const debouncedFetch = debounce((query) => {
  fetchResults(query);
}, 300);   // 300ms delay

searchInput.addEventListener('input', (e) => {
  debouncedFetch(e.target.value);
});
```

Now `fetchResults` will only be called **once**, 300ms after the user stops typing.

---

## 3. Complete working example

Here’s a full HTML page demonstrating the concept (the API call is simulated with a `console.log`):

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Debounced Search</title>
</head>
<body>
